"We really wanted to win and not be potato, but maybe we wanted it too much. We caught the start, but we couldn't keep it because they rolled us under the basket, " regretted captain Karolína malečková. "Playing in front of such an audience was an incredible experience," she praised the fans in Klatovy and Pilsen.
The Czechs started very well, thanks to two threes they took the lead 8: 0 and dominated the entire first quarter on the court. At that moment, it seemed that the opponents would pay off the defeat from the base group 85: 88 after overtime. However, the referee whistled 15 fouls during the half and with questionable decisions helped Hungary to return to the game with a 12:2 lead.
"I am convinced that it was enough to put two more three baskets, run away to 20 points and we would not let it go. But instead came our mistakes. I'm not interested in the referees, but what we did wrong, and there were mistakes that helped the opponent to catch, " evaluated coach Richard Fousek.
"It was not the first time we had a lapse in concentration. But the girls are fighters, they did not let anything out and fought to the end. But the opponent was very good, " he added.
The Czechs kept in the game especially Petra holešínská accurate shooting from a distance and pivotka Tereza šípová. However, the Czech top scorer had a problem with fouls and missed much of the third quarter on the court. The Hungarians took advantage of this and gained a slight lead, which they already kept, although the Czechs fought until the last seconds.
"For us, the first five matches were very difficult, we rotated the matches in a narrow rotation and it cost us a lot of strength. Already against Spain, you could see that the girls were tired and there was nowhere to take. Because of the physicality, we weren't consistent defensively. We didn't play a quick counterattack, we missed a rebound. And the Hungarians are so good that if you don't put everything together, it's hard to win, " added Fousek.
He believes that a promising future awaits his ward. "In two years, the girls were able to win the Youth Olympics, to be second at the European Championship of sixteen-year-olds, and now they are fourth in the world. It is a quality team with a good character and we need to continue to work with it and develop talent. Now it is up to the federation which coach will be assigned to them in the higher categories, " added Fousek.
