The Brno company developing CCV software is facing legal action from the Finnish manufacturer of telecommunications equipment Nokia. Finns do not like that the program of the Brno company for warehouse management is called Lokia WMS, wrote the daily E15. Therefore, Nokia filed objections to the application of the Lokia brand to the industrial property office. The CCV considers that substitution is unlikely.
Marketing director Petr ondrášek said that the program is already used by two dozen customers, it has been on the market since last September.
"The Nokia brand enjoys recognition and trust around the world. When someone attempts to register a trademark that we believe may lead to confusion or weakening of our brand, we take steps to protect our valuable asset," said Nokia spokesman Mark Durrant.
Brno developers claim that they did not think about the brand famous in the past by mobile phones when creating a warehouse program. The designation Lokia according to ccv is based on the Latin name for one species of Dragonfly, whose rapid movement is supposed to be an analogue of the movement of storekeepers around the warehouse.
"In the Czech market, the possibility of substitution is unlikely. We sell modern cloud software with which companies equip their warehouse operations, and we are not really heading into the field of mobile phone production. And we do not want to be compared to a brand that may be running out of steam in its field, " CCV manager Tomáš kormaňák responded in E15.
Ccv applied for trademark protection in August before the launch of the programme at the industrial property office. "Protection was sought for products and services in classes 9, 35 and 42, since software belongs to class 9, related warehouse business management services belong to class 35 and computer software development to class 42 according to the international classification," said ondrášek.
Nokia's objection is based on the fact that the earlier Nokia trade mark is valid in all classes of goods and services and thus covers the widest possible range of goods and services and therefore, of course, overlaps also in classes 9, 35 and 42. 'The CCV does not dispute the claim of the objector as regards the conformity of those classes of products and services. In reality, however, these are completely different brands aimed at other target groups, " said ondrášek.
The dispute over the brand can take months, according to E15, and this can complicate the company's activities.
