Epilepsy complicated his love of sports, thanks to the operation he has a new hope
For the first time, the parents of Honzik noticed that something was wrong with him, in a year and a half. He always looked into space for a few minutes, became immobile and did not react to anyone. Therefore, the pediatrician sent him to the children's neurological clinic, where doctors diagnosed him with epilepsy after a series of examinations and immediately put him on medication, which did not work immediately.
It took almost a year for the doctors to find the ideal combination of drugs, thanks to which he completely stopped having seizures. At the age of five, doctors stopped him from taking medication, and since the seizures did not return, his parents thought that Honza was healthy and began to lead him more to sports. He rode a bicycle, skied, played tennis and floorball, spent his free time playing with his sister and friends. But at the age of eleven, he had another seizure, and everything started all over again.
Doctors again tried different combinations of drugs, but this time nothing worked anymore, seizures in the form of absences were constantly repeated. Since he always lost his senses during a seizure, his parents were terrified that he would get it during sports and get injured. Gradually, Honza stopped cycling and replaced downhill skis with cross-country skis and snowboard. Although from time to time the sport gave him a fit, he never completely gave it up. He even fulfilled his dream and finished the Spartan race, but together with a friend who had him constantly in sight to help in case of an emergency.
When Honza was 15 years old, his parents decided to try to change doctors and turned to specialists in the FN in Motol. The doctors there, after a series of examinations, concluded that Honza was a candidate for surgery to remove a lesion from his brain-the source of epileptic seizures. "I had 2 operations in a row, first the doctors inserted probes into my brain that sensed its activity, then they could only remove the bearing. It's been a few weeks of hell for me. I just had to lie down and hardly move, wires sticking out of my head, which were connected to the computer, " recalls Honza.
The operation was successful, and the doctors removed a fairly extensive bearing. "The first days after the operation it was very mentally demanding, Honza was apathetic, confused, sad and almost did not speak. As opposed to how he is normally alive and communicative, this was a scary change, but fortunately, after a couple of days everything returned to normal, "the mom describes, adding:" a month and a half after the operation, he had 1 seizure, but according to doctors, it happens. He's been seizure-free for three months."
This school year, Honza will graduate, in addition to sports, he enjoys languages and began to cooperate with the company E, with which he travels around schools for discussions about epilepsy. Honza is not yet fully engaged in sports activities, he is starting to return to the sport gradually. "I learn how to play sports properly, how to breathe well, so as not to expose the body to sudden stress, which, however, is quite a challenge with my competitive nature," explains Honza.
This year, therefore, will not actively participate in the traditional EPPI water triathlon, which meets patients with epilepsy and healthy athletes, and which takes place this weekend 28. September 2019 at veselská piskovna. But maybe next year.
