Microplastics have reached the human intestines, confirmed for the first time a study
Scientists have confirmed several years of suspicion. A team led by Vienna University Professor Philipp Schwabl has published a study that for the first time proves the presence of microplastics in human stool. Although the study is small, with eight participants from Europe, Japan and Russia-however, tiny plastic particles measuring between 50 and 500 micrometers were found in the samples of all subjects studied. None of the eight subjects were vegetarian, six of them did not avoid sea fish, all drank water from plastic bottles and food packed in plastic.
And it would actually be kind of a miracle if nothing was found. We already know that microplastics - which are either produced directly, for example for the cosmetics industry, or produced by breaking up larger pieces-are present in marine animals, insects, tap water and sodas; in short, everywhere on the planet. Thus, their entry into the digestive system of man is only officially confirmed. There were about 20 microplastic particles per ten grams of stool, and scientists estimate that more than half of the world's population will have them.
Of course, both lay and scientific awareness knows that this is not good. However, humanity still does not know how bad it is-and what effect microplastics have on the "host" organisms. Small particles can get into the bloodstream or the lymphatic system and end up, for example, in the liver. "This is the first ever study of its kind and has confirmed what we have long thought. Now that we have the first evidence of the occurrence of microplastics in the human body, we must continue to investigate what exactly this means for human health, " says Schwabl.
So far, it is known that microplastics in the intestines can negatively affect the immune reactions of the digestive system, thereby facilitating the absorption of poisonous chemicals and other pathogens into the body. And so far, no other solution is known than to limit the use of plastics, especially polypropylene. However, this will be difficult-the first task facing governments and authorities will at least be to stop its steep increase. As for plastic bottles alone, experts estimate that in three years, humanity will consume a fifth more than today. The current rate is a staggering million bottles bought per minute. Around eight million tonnes of plastic end up in the seas and oceans every year. Waste threatens marine ecosystems and infects the digestive systems of marine animals.
Some countries have already adopted restrictions and other measures, Kenya, for example, has banned plastic bags under the threat of draconian penalties. The European Commission is considering small-scale bans (the well-known straws), and the domestic Ministry of the environment is heading in the same direction. But critics say that such measures, while Nice, are completely inadequate.
Repair of the Krkonoše museum will be a year late
The Krkonoše national park administration (krnap) has postponed the deadline for submitting bids for the second tender for the repair of the Krkonoše museum in Vrchlabí by three weeks. The original date for opening envelopes was 20. September, said national park spokesman Radek drahny. The reason for the postponement of the deadline for the submission of tenders is the reduction of the budget from CZK 110 million to CZK 83 million.
"At the moment we are working with the prices that are on the market. There has been a change in the budget, this is the price we expect to be offered. If someone submits an offer that will be acceptable, then the work will begin as soon as possible, " said Dear.
Compared to the original plans, the start of the repair of the museum is about a year late. Krnap wanted to have a selected supplier of construction parts by the end of last year and start construction work this spring. According to the management of the national park administration, European subsidies of CZK 123 million for the project are not threatened.
Krnap administration is unable to choose a construction company for the repair of the museum. The second tender was launched this summer, because in the previous tender all offers of companies significantly exceeded the then estimated price of 65 million. The bids exceeded 100 million crowns.
The museum, which is housed in a former Augustinian monastery and belongs to the krnap administration, has been closed since autumn 2017. The selected firm should provide the construction part of the project. The total cost, including the construction of a new exposition, is estimated at CZK 210 million. The krnap visitor center should be built in the now vacated building by the end of 2021 after the transformation of the expositions.
The repaired museum with a new interactive exposition, which should be a story of nature and people settled in the mountains and build on the successful exposition stone and life, should serve as a representative entrance gate of the giant mountains for visitors. The visitor center should provide the most understandable form of information about the past and present of the giant mountains and motivate people to discover the mountains and protect them. It should also assume the role of a traditional museum. The center will also offer opportunities to organize concerts, festivals, theatrical performances or lectures in the open air. The plans include the construction of a new entrance to the building, the establishment of a study or cafe.
On Saturday, česká spořitelna erroneously charged some card payments twice.
The error has already been fixed
Česká spořitelna erroneously charged some card payments twice to its clients on Saturday afternoon.
According to the bank's spokesman Lukáš kropík, the problem could have involved thousands of transactions.
The error has already been corrected by the savings bank and the money returned to the clients.
Problems with double billing of card payments the savings bank noticed on Saturday afternoon.
"Just yesterday (Saturday) night, we updated the system and immediately returned all these double payments to our clients.
At the moment everything works without problems, " said Kropík on Sunday afternoon.
The exact number of clients to whom the bank deducted money from card payments twice, the spokesman of the bank does not know, according to his estimate, these were lower thousands of transactions.
The causes of problems are being investigated by the savings bank.
"It could have been a combination of several factors," said kropik.
Česká spořitelna is the largest bank in the Czech Republic by number of clients.
At the end of March, she had 4.6 million.
The owner of the savings bank is the Austrian financial group Erste Group Bank, which is a key player in the banking market of central and eastern Europe.
