Francis Fukuyama's history is kind of baked in. In 1992, at the height of the wave of liberalism that followed the end of the Cold War and the fall of the Iron Curtain, this political scientist wrote in his most famous book the end of history and the last man: "what we may be witnessing... it is the final point of the ideological development of mankind and the universal acceptance of Western liberal democracy as the final form of government."
Twenty-six years later, we are seeing rather illiberal models triumph from the US to Russia, from Turkey to Poland, and from Hungary to Italy, and various forms of nationalism and radicalism flourish. Fukuyama's current ninth book, identity: the demand for Dignity and the politics of Resentment, attempts to balance these forces. As his interview with George Eaton for the New Statesman shows, he reconsiders many of his former positions: he argues that the ideas of socialism should be returned to the public space, and Marx was right in many respects. At the same time, he insists that his intellectual development is still in line with the position of the 1990s, and critics have not understood the end of history and the last man correctly.
"What I said back then was that one of the problems of modern democracy is that while it provides peace and prosperity, people want more than that... Liberal democracies do not even try to define what a good life is. It leaves it to individuals who feel alienated, do not see the point, and therefore group themselves into groups according to identity that give them a sense of belonging."
In its time, the book the end of history and the last man was written as a strong argument against the Marxists, who perceived communism as the final stage of history. When Fukuyama is asked how he now sees the rise of socialists in Britain and the US, he replies: "it all depends on what you mean by socialism. If we are talking about ownership of the means of production, then, in my opinion, this will not work, except when clear public services are in demand. But if you mean redistributive programs that are trying to solve the huge imbalance in income and wealth that we are already seeing, then yes. I think not only could he come back, he should come back. The long period that President Reagan and prime minister Thatcher started, in which certain types of ideas about the benefits of an unregulated market came to the fore, has had a disastrous effect in many ways."
In the end, Fukuyama tries to calm the current situation, warning all liberals that even the advent of new, not entirely democratic regimes will not mean the end of history.
Civilization in the allotted time
Recently, I remembered a beautiful "line" from one of the great stories of Simek with Grossman, which takes place partly in the cemetery, which reads as follows: "I warned her that she cries well, but on someone else's grave!"It occurred to me that many world politicians engaged in the senseless fight against climate change are now behaving very similarly.
They behave as if the planet earth is ruled by humans. In fact, we are just a speck on its surface, which it can blow out with its enormous forces like a sharp gust of wind the flame of a candle. Perhaps few of them look at the famous British and American natural science documents discussing the destructive capabilities of our blue ball. After all, it would be enough for one of the larger active volcanoes to properly" blow up " and our advanced civilization will fall from it.
And that this will happen in the near future is highly likely. A number of large volcanoes have, according to leading volcanologists, "charged and unlocked" (for example, Katla in Iceland).
In a way, it would be ideal if the eruption, if it must happen once, occurred as soon as possible. Even before trillions of dollars are wasted on measures to reduce carbon dioxide production, because any really angry volcano, along with dust and poisonous volcanic gases, can release at least a hundred times more into the atmosphere than has been saved at the expense of the people of Europe.
Therefore, it makes no sense to restrict CO2 production by force. In addition, it has been scientifically proven that with its significantly higher proportion in the air, plants form more biological matter and are also more drought-resistant. For humanity, possible warming is significantly more favorable than, for example, a rapid return of the ice age.
Bearing in mind the still insufficiently studied influence of the solar cycles on the earth's climate, there is only one reasonable conclusion to be drawn: let us strive to keep the earth as clean as possible, and let us try to adapt to other changes with which we cannot cope with the force with the least cost!
