Declaration of the end of the right in the house or what "right" coalition ODS, TOP 09, Stan and KDU?
In the media and comments recently there are reports about the upcoming coalition of the parties mentioned. Many are applauding that the 'right' is finally coming together, but I am more interested in why these parties still identify themselves as right-wing.
Apart from the new Tricolor movement, the Czech Chamber of Deputies no longer has a real right-wing party. And it does not matter how the subjects themselves refer to themselves or what label the mainstream media parrot. The ODS is hardly centrist in its average of top politicians of this party, the top 09 is clearly the party of the urban pseudo-liberal left (which is ashamed of its leftism and thus hypocritically refers to itself as conservative or even right-wing). Stan is a party that, by its concept, ideology and voter targeting, basically merges with TOP 09 (the reason for its existence is simply not clear to me). And the KDU has even long labeled itself as a center-left party-but their political compass is much more to the left than they say.
Do you feel like I took them all out of the water? No, I am based on the real political actions of these parties. If I consider myself a classically liberal right-wing voter, the highest value for me is the freedom of the individual, the free market and minimal state interference in the life of individuals and the economy. How do they fulfil this general assumption of right-handedness? How many laws cutting people's freedoms with a sausage sizzle, raising taxes, confirming new regulations and increasing surveillance, increasing ties to a socialist EU, or promoting environmental and gender madness in recent years? Very, very much. Not their own labels, but actions identify them. These parties, despite all sorts of declarations or partial concessions, want to strengthen the role of the state in our lives. And that has nothing to do with being right-wing.
Coalition cooperation TOP 09, Stan and KDU I would not be surprised at all, on the political map they simply belong to each other and, except for Christian or, on the contrary, homosexual and gender aspects, I do not see any obvious difference for voters in terms of the influence of the state on their lives. However, the ODS has long portrayed itself as "the only right-wing party", and by associating with these three entities, it no longer reveals its true political affiliation.
By the way, when I briefly mentioned the stickers. Have you noticed how often all these parties consistently and cheaply refer to critics of dirigism and socialism coming from the European Union as pro-Russian agents? Are they unable or unwilling to understand that there are many people to whom eurosocialism and growing inequality do not smell as strongly as the authoritarian regime in Russia? Do they not by any chance hide their utter inability to argue and their groundless or blind adoration of the euro-union situation?
In short, it is possible that in the Czech Republic, politics other than the center no longer has a chance of greater success. Maybe that's what the voters really want. Perhaps they want left-wing politics under the cloak of the "right" because they are ashamed of their political beliefs (or they cannot even identify them). I don't know. I'm certainly not one of those voters.
