Bloomberg: Venezuela has hidden Bitcoins and does not know what to do with them
The central bank of Venezuela conducts internal tests to determine whether it can hold cryptocurrencies. It responds to an instruction from the state-owned company Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which seeks to be able to send bitcoins and ethers to the central bank, and then the bank pays the suppliers of this oil company with cryptocurrencies. Employees are also studying the proposal to allow the central bank to count cryptocurrencies in foreign exchange reserves, which are now close to the minimum in 30 years. Citing information from four sources, this was reported by Bloomberg.
The sanctions imposed by the United States against the authoritarian regime of President Nicolás Maduro have largely cut Venezuela off from the global financial system. This further exacerbated the economic crisis in the country. Meanwhile, the current crisis is one of the most serious in global comparison, forcing officials to use a mixture of different ways to move money. While Maduro's effort to launch the world's first state-owned cryptocurrency has failed, ongoing efforts to use digital currencies show how desperate the government is to find ways around the restrictions.
Neither the central bank of Venezuela nor PDVSA responded to a request for comment.
It is not clear how PDVSA came to own bitcoins and ethers, nor how much value these currencies possess. The enterprise has problems obtaining payments from customers through conventional channels, since large banks are not willing to do business with entities subject to sanctions. Last month, the company received most of the payment of 700 million dollars (16.6 billion rubles) in Chinese yuan, because the parties could not find financial institutions that would allow the transaction.
PDVSA may not have the appetite to sell cryptocurrencies on the open market, as this would require it to register on the exchange and undergo an in-depth review, the so-called due diligence. Instead, it wants the central bank to use the cryptocurrency and pay with it the entities to which PDVSA owes. Representatives of the oil company believe that the central bank is less exposed to possible obstacles that could arise when making payments with crypto-currencies.
Bitcoins and ethers use a decentralized internet ledger known as blockchain to verify and record transactions. In some cases, relatively anonymous transfers are possible without the need for an intermediary. Few banks engage in digital currencies because of the money laundering and client information problems associated with them, complicating compliance.
Cryptocurrencies, after the debacle of 2018, are experiencing a return to the limelight this year thanks to the expectation of their greater acceptance by institutions and Facebook's plan to come up with its own cryptocurrency. Even so, they remain unstable. Bitcoin has fallen almost 20 percent over the past four days, however, since the beginning of the year it has a gain of about 130 percent.
