The library commemorates the anniversary of the death of Wenceslas IV. exhibition of manuscripts
Six rare historical manuscripts from the turn of the 14th century. and 15. 19th century, that is, from the time of the Roman and Czech King Václav IV., can be viewed today and Saturday by people in Prague's Klementinum. The National Library released them from their vaults to commemorate this year's 600. anniversary of Václav's death. This morning, librarians and restorers placed rare originals in display cases in the mirror chapel. Admission to the exhibition is free, it is open on both days from 10: 00 to 18: 00.
Exhibition of documents entitled ad Mandatum Domini Regis: from the royal office and library of Wenceslas IV. prepared by the library together with the National Archives. Written heritage from the reign of Wenceslas IV. the national archive looks from the point of view of official documents and the National Library from the point of view of literary works, its author Jan vojtíšek said about the exhibition.
"Visitors can look forward to, for example, a work on agriculture by Peter de crescentiis, which is essentially an encyclopedia of agriculture, or a breviary, a prayer book of one of the Benedictine monks of the monastery of St. George in Prague Castle, from the beginning of the 15th century. he listed the reasons why people should look at the exhibition, according to him.
The epistles of Peter of Blois will also be exhibited, where the semi-figure of the English king Henry II is depicted in the opening miniature h (enrico). The author of the decoration is most likely the master of Samson's history, who, in addition to the two volumes of the bible of Wenceslas IV. he also participated in the decoration of a number of other manuscripts. Visitors will also see a Latin anthology of John Wycliff's treatises from about 1411 to 1414.
From the library of Wenceslas IV. not a single book has been preserved in the Czech territory. This library, according to experts, was one of the most extensive and also the most beautiful book collections in central Europe at that time, because the young king wanted to build a representative library that would match the book collections of his French relatives. However, the library ceased to exist soon after Václav's death. Apparently, it was looted or destroyed during the conquest of the castle by the Hussites. But several codes were saved. Most of them are now owned by the Austrian national library.
"We have a number of treasures in our collections and I am glad that they are in a state that allows them to be exhibited and made available to the public so-called Live and not only in the form of the Digital Library Manuscriptorium," said the director of the National Library Martin Kocanda.
On the day of Saturday's national holiday, an exhibition entitled What is hidden under the floor, which presents local archaeological discoveries, will also be opened free of charge in Klementinum.
