Destroyed shops, fires in the streets, a memorial procession accompanied by riots
Five years ago, 43 students of Ayotzinapa university disappeared, despite an extensive investigation, the case has not yet been clarified. Allegedly, the students were to be detained by the police in the Mexican state of Guerrero. It is not clear exactly what happened next, according to the investigation, but the students apparently ended up in the hands of a local syndicate and were subsequently killed and burned, APTN reports.
On Thursday, a memorial procession was held in Mexico's capital, families wanted to express their frustration at the fact that they still could not find answers and explain the disappearance of their children.
The mostly peaceful march was disrupted by smaller groups of vandals, who destroyed everything in their path. Vandals destroyed shops and hotels, did not hesitate to destroy monuments, set fires around the city and blew out windows.
Even before the march, president Andres Manuel López Obrador said that he would do everything to catch them, and asked the public for any information that would lead to clarification of the case.
