Specification means a precise description of the application, its features, functionalities and user interface, which forms Annex 3 (description of the application components and documentation).
An upgrade means an incremental change to an application that enables the deployment of new functionality, a change to an existing functionality, or a change to the data in the application from the current state of the application. The upgrade consists of those requisites of the version in which there was a change from the current state of the application. The upgrade also includes a description of how to test for the new functionality contained in it. The current state of the application is obtained by installing the last delivered version and all subsequent upgrades, and as part of the deployment of the upgrade, all patches that have been created since the previous upgrade are also deployed, except for those that have not modified the functionality or control data of the application. The upgrade also includes the relevant documentation. The upgrade includes customer-specified changes to the application implemented on the basis of the change documentation and incident resolution of category C.
Version means the complete state of the application in a form that allows a complete and separate installation of the application, including its settings, in order to provide functionality in terms of specifications and operational settings. The version includes (1) the version of the application in the form of executable codes; and (2) the operating settings of the application; and (3) the documentation of the application.
Change management is the procedure by which a change in the application and documentation is made. The result of the change management is a change in the application and documentation that is consistent with the change request.
