Annex 7 / classification of incidents
The items below are for inspiration only.  This annex must be accurately and exhaustively formulated by the project manager.
Operational environment incidents
An Incident of Category A means an Incident in an operational environment if to an example:
the user cannot log in to the application
when an application repeatedly crashes on the same step and the user cannot complete the critical process
when the system shows too long (twice the defined performance parameters)
user activity responses
when it is not possible to print documentation or report for the client
when the end customer is shown incorrect data
The critical functionalities/processes of the application are:
opening or closing an account
starting the Daily shutter
An Incident of Category B means an Incident in an operational environment if to the example:
the work of the user is slowed down, but it does not have a serious effect on compliance with the workflow
when non-critical functionality is unavailable to the end customer.
An Incident of Category C means an Incident in an operating environment if to the example:
when it is a language defect, or a font other than the agreed font
when it is a graphics error in the user interface that does not confuse the user in the use of the interface
when there is a defect in the documentation
Incidents from the acceptance environment
Incident category TA means an Incident in an acceptance environment if to an example:
unable to start client on system
An Incident of category TB means an Incident in an acceptance environment if to the example:
Cannot change any client account parameter
An Incident of the TC category means an Incident in the acceptance environment if to the example:
when it is a language defect, or a font other than the agreed font
when it is a graphics error in the user interface that does not confuse the user in the use of the interface
when there is a defect in the documentation
