Museum in sEmily with an exhibition returns to the Velvet Revolution
Imitation of a normalization room with a TV in which footage of the brutal crackdown of police officers against students from 17. November 1989 in Prague. This, too, is in the new exhibition of the museum in sEmily, which is dedicated to the velvet revolution. "The basis is to imagine what happened in sEmily after the events at Národní třída," said Tomáš chvátal, curator of the exhibition.
"I would say that the atmosphere was basically the same everywhere with the fact that the first demonstration was held in sEmily on 22. November, and then every day gradually packed up more people," he said. Among the most active were at first a group of local dissidents around Miroslav matěcha, who was the only one from the city and the immediate vicinity to sign Charter 77, and the spouses of the grandfathers, who spread the petition several sentences. According to chvátal, the civic forum was also formed relatively quickly. "One of the specifics is that there was a very strong group of local doctors in the civic forum," said the curator.
Visitors should be drawn into the current events in the city by about 50 photographs, taken 30 years ago by Karel bárta. A video of the 27th general strike has also been preserved. November 1989 filmed by František tomíček, which will be played in the loop throughout the exhibition. At the demonstration, Ivan the voice also spoke and sang. The semilsk archive also lent a number of preserved banners to the exhibition. "They said: let's not get drunk with a roll, from trough to trough, we do not want violence," chvátal said. Some changes in the city were very rapid at that time, for example, already in December the people in the All-Russian vote decided that the square would be riegrovo and abolished the previous name gottwaldovo.
The exhibition also captures the events before the November events. "In the first part, we present to the contemporaries and students what was before, such a late normalization. I think we managed to collect unique documents from Semil, whether they are banners with various communist slogans or a bronze plaque from the Museum of the workers ' movement at that time," chvátal said. One room is supposed to evoke the feeling of what it might have looked like in the living room of an ordinary household.
The last part of the exhibition, in turn, is devoted to what was after the velvet revolution. It is aimed at the first free elections. "We papered one room with election posters. Those who have experienced it will remember the posters with us to Europe or there is Václav Klaus still under the heading OF with a beautiful motto each for his village," added the curator.
Pike in a pond, or a relatively prosperous open-air museum?
Babiš chose for his optimistic view statistics such as good security (the Czech Republic is the seventh in the world), low unemployment rate, low national debt. Or the fact that our country, according to one recent study, is 24th in quality of life out of 140 countries evaluated.
However, the developer Dušan kunovský and the architect Josef pleskot, in a television interview on the occasion of the summit of architecture and development, presented other, not so "rosy" data. For example, that the Czech Republic is at 154. place in the world in the speed of construction management. It may be that the current economic "boom" will not leave behind any significant building heritage, as it was in the past.
The biggest obstacle is not only existing legislation, but also a slow, inefficient bureaucracy. This is also documented by comparative studies, in which the Czech Republic lags significantly behind developed countries in the overall quality and performance of public administration.
Our country has simply not yet been able to make good use of the potential of the good economic situation of recent years to invest in the future. It is nice that salaries and pensions are increasing, but people with an improving standard of living will also want to have somewhere to live, to travel modern and fast, to have quality cultural stands, to live without the unbearable environmental burden.
But in the capital city of Prague, for example, it has not been possible for years to complete the inner and outer ring road or build an expressway or metro to the airport. And Prague does not even have a modern, architecturally daring national library, concert hall, or National Gallery. The reason for this is not only absurd scramble for architectural competitions, zoning plans and building permits, but also a kind of specifically Czech conservatism, which adheres to the motto "every bolder change is for the worse".
And when it seems that something more daring could succeed, it will almost certainly be thwarted by the monuments men or other rather well-intentioned associations, or politicians. In the absurd drama surrounding Jan Kaplický's" blob " proposed for the new building of the National Library, president Václav Klaus even wanted to tie himself to the dredgers.
However, the list does not end with a threshold. The Czech Republic is not able to complete its backbone motorway network, nor to start building high-speed trains, so Germany finally decided to run its tracks for superfast trains from Berlin to Vienna by "detour" through Bavaria. In addition, in šlendrián, repairs to existing infrastructure are often carried out. Getting from Prague to Brno quickly is now a done deal.
Babiš came into politics promising to "get things done". But not much has happened yet when it comes to meaningful investment and speeding up cumbersome bureaucratic procedures. Since 2018, an amendment to the law on speeding up the construction of transport infrastructure is in force, but we will have to wait for more extensive beneficial effects, such as easier land expropriation. And the new building code, approved by the government, which is supposed to reduce the current average length of construction proceedings from 5.4 years to one year, will, if we are lucky, start to apply from 2021. I don't think a lot of people would bet on that.
