The launch of the new toll is not threatened, reports the Kremlin. But there is a change of operator in the game
The Ministry of transport on Friday began preparations for a new tender for the operation of the new toll system. This is a backup plan that the state would use in the event that the current toll contract was finally terminated. In addition, the state is also preparing other provisional solutions in case the tender could not be completed on time. On Facebook, this was stated by Transport Minister Vladimir kremlik (for yes).
The office for the protection of competition (úohs) on Thursday banned the performance of the toll contract between the state and the CzechToll/skytoll consortium, with a one-year delay. The ministry will file a lawsuit against it.
"The launch of the new toll collection system is not threatened. Starting today, we are launching the preparation of a new transparent tender, the subject of which will be the services of the operation of the new toll system, which is now being finalized by the CzechToll and skytoll consortium," the minister said.
Thus, the state would look for the operator of the currently prepared toll in the tender, which will be launched from this December. So it would not be a competition for a completely new toll system, as was the case with the last tender, nor the use of the old system, which is now operated by Kapsch.
However, according to the Kremlin, the ministry is also preparing for the fact that it would not be able to prepare a new tender in time. "Based on my experience with the toll tender process, I am deeply convinced that the úohs is wrong and that it is objectively impossible to prepare and implement such a complex tender procedure and transfer the operation of the toll system to a new operator within the 12-month period," he said.
In addition to the new tender procedure, the resort will also prepare a provisional solution that would solve the toll collection for a transitional period until the state finds a full-fledged form of solution.
Thus, the state will probably not take advantage of the offer presented to it by the current toll administrator Kapsch in the past few days. An Austrian company offered the state to operate the existing system in case the toll contract was cancelled.
At the same time, the Kremlin reiterated that it believes that a backup plan will not be needed. Therefore, the ministry will file an appeal against the decision of the antimonopoly authority.
On Thursday, the úohs issued a decision in which it banned the performance of the toll contract. But the ban will come into force only one year after the legal force of the decision of the authority. This is not final and can be appealed to the president of the office. The ministry and CzechToll are therefore continuing to prepare the new toll, which should be launched in December.
The CzechToll/skytoll consortium won last year's tender for a new toll system and its operator. It succeeded in a toll tender with a bid of 10.75 billion crowns for a ten-year operation. The current operator Kapsch protested against the tender process and the validity of the toll contract, which failed in the tender with an offer of over CZK 13 billion.
