No other animal class is more represented in nature than insects. Beetles, butterflies and other species make up more than half of life on earth. But reports are mounting that the insect kingdom is drastically shrinking. Another scientific study on this topic came out just this week, and the situation, according to her, is even more serious than humanity has realized so far.
The study is based on field research in the tropical rainforest of Puerto Rico, in which American scientists copied a similar survey from 1976. As they write right at the beginning of the report, insects are now in the forest "ten to sixty times less". This is a decline in the entire population, not the number of species, and the research concerned not only insects, but all arthropods. Due to the extinction of insects, the population of other fauna that are dependent on insects in the food chain, such as birds, frogs or lizards, is also thinning.
The authors of the research put their conclusions in direct connection with climate change. According to them, the average air temperature in the forest has risen by two degrees Celsius in the last thirty years, and warming has become the driving force behind the collapse of the food chain. Thus, according to the author's team, the study shows that the impact of climate change on tropical ecosystems may be much greater than previously thought.
The report was published on Monday in a large article in the Washington Post, which makes the new findings immediately in the headline as hyper-alarming. "It's one of the most disturbing articles I've ever read," entomologist David Wagner of the University of Connecticut, whom the paper cites as an independent expert, told the paper.
The extinction of insects also concerns Europe. "In our country, the decline is also an order of magnitude," says Lukáš čížek from the Entomological Institute of the Academy of Sciences. However, in addition to climate change, it is necessary to take into account the landscape changes that play an essential role in Europe. "In our country only runs significantly longer than in Puerto Rico," adds Čížek to explain why in the rainforest compared to 70. years ago, scientists could measure such a rapid decline.
