"So it turns out that young Czechs have a little more confidence in their knowledge of finance than reality. In this case, women and respondents without a high school diploma had a significantly higher proportion of wrong answers," said Jaroslava palendalová, director of Kruk.
Men and young high school or college students are more likely to trust their knowledge of financial products.
Young Czechs learn most about the functioning of financial affairs from parents (37 percent), self-study on the internet (23 percent) and only in the third place from teaching at school (21 percent).
Questions around finances consult with parents mainly women, while information on the internet is more often sought by men. Obtaining information about finances from parents prevails in all age categories of young people, regardless of their educational attainment or personal income. Practically minimal influence is exerted by prospectuses of financial institutions, professional journals and publications.
