The US Anti-Doping Agency (USADA) closed his case in early September without filing charges due to formal reasons. Coleman did not pass three doping tests last year and this year, but not in 12 months. His first offense, the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) dated back to 1. April 2018, that is, to the beginning of the second quarter, however, the test itself missed up to 6. June. And because the third omission occurred on the 29th. on April 20, 2019, Coleman did not commit a misdemeanor in the form of three failed inspections within 12 months.
Coleman argued that he only forgot to update the data in the application about the whereabouts of athletes. "I don't do drugs, I don't do anything legal. A lot of athletes take legal creatine or protein powder or various other supplements for faster recovery. And I don't take anything, I work hard and that's what it's about, " he said before the start of the World Cup.
The only defeat from six starts this year on the hundred was suffered right at the start of the season at the Diamond League in Shanghai, where he was only six thousandths of a second ahead of compatriot Noah Lyles. He took advantage of Coleman's absence to triumph in the Diamond League final, but will only run a double hundred at the World Cup.
On paper, the second fastest competitor with a performance of 9.86 is 22-year-old Nigerian Divine Oduduru, who has so far succeeded only in American university competitions.
Defending the title will be the thirty-seven-year-old American Justin Gatlin, who in June at Stanford flashed with a time of 9.87. He ran the last 100 in Zagreb but only in 10.29 because he slightly injured his back thigh muscle.
The favorites also include South African Akani Simbine, three-time Olympic medalist from Rio Andre De Grasse or European champion Zharnel Hughes. The fastest Jamaican is the 2011 world champion Yohan Blake with a time of 9.96.
The men's 100 starts on Friday with the preliminaries and heats. Semi-finals and finals are on the agenda on Saturday. The medals will be competed at 21: 15 CEST.
EU countries have coronavirus standards for aviation
European Union countries have agreed on common sanitary standards for air travel to help limit the spread of the new coronavirus.
This was announced by German Transport Minister Andreas Scheuer.
Among the agreed standards is the observance of distance or wearing of veils on the plane and at the airport, but the middle seats in airplanes will not have to remain unoccupied.
This was reported by Reuters.
"I am glad that my colleagues accepted the German proposal for Europe and that we were able to agree on these uniform standards," Scheuer said at the European aviation conference.
The German transport ministry then added that the agreement had been concluded by officials and that it still had to be formally approved by ministers.
The agreed measures include the requirement to cover the mouth and nose for passengers from the age of six, to observe the recommended distance during security checks and check-in at the airport.
There must also be sufficient fresh air on the aircraft and all information must be available in several languages.
The airlines will also be able to occupy the middle seats.
The common rules that officials have agreed on Meet at least some of the requirements of airlines.
