The soldiers are rehearsing, draw the curtains. China is preparing celebrations at the site of the massacre
The army has been rehearsing the parade over recent weekends. Shops in the center of Beijing had to close, and residents near the square were ordered to close the curtains. On the empty streets, military vehicles rolled towards the square, and warplanes circled in the sky.
Several Chinese told Reuters they were proud of their country's military prowess. But one woman said that it was hard to deny that the celebrations would upset other countries.
Apparently, she was referring to Taiwan, which China claims and where elections are approaching. But they may also have concerns in the semi-autonomous city of Hong Kong, where thousands of people have repeatedly demonstrated against the Chinese-appointed administrator.
Celebrations are also being prepared outside Beijing. The South China Sea port of Xiamen has already shown a special light show on Thursday night. Located opposite the island of Taiwan, Xiamen is one of China's ten most innovative cities.
Before the anniversary, the list of prohibited things is growing. Already on it are drones, balloons, kites, alcohol, walkie-talkies and devices using radio waves, the Guardian newspaper pointed out. He added that the popular Chinese social network Weibo erases"harmful political information."
"This is another milestone, another opportunity to show that the Chinese Communist Party remains (at the OAR) despite all the predictions," said historian Maura Cunningham, who studies China. "This is a moment when the party can demonstrate order, control and power," she added.
The people's Republic of China was formed in 1949, when the communists under the leadership of Mao Zedong won in the struggle with the Chiang Kai-shek nationalists, who retreated to Taiwan.
In the second half of 60. for years, China underwent a disastrous communist experiment in the form of a so-called cultural revolution. In June 1989, the Tiananmen Square regime massacred thousands of pro-democracy protesters, both students and workers, with tanks.
Since the late 70's. for years, China has increasingly taken over the elements of the capitalist economy. According to critics, it is now a mixture of the worst of communism (the monopoly of one party and the persecution of the opposition) and (Dickensian) capitalism (the exploitation of workers).
