Uncombed wants $ 45 million from the state.
The Ministry of justice, according to the spokesman of the office of Vladimir řepka, has received six applications in this regard so far and is now analyzing them. The young man was imprisoned for two years for assaulting a woman, but the justice finally exonerated him.
Both the chief prosecutor Pavel Zeman and the minister of justice Marie benešová did not appeal in the case.
The attempted murder of a hairdresser in hořice happened in February 2013. The Hradec state prosecutor's office indicted the then 20-year-old student of the grammar school Nečesaný. The prosecution claimed that he hit the woman several times in the head with a log and then took over ten thousand crowns from her. The seriously injured woman was found by her son, her life was saved by the doctors of the Hradec hospital.
Uncombed from the beginning, he denied any guilt. "I am innocent, and I swear to it. I am sincerely sorry for what happened to the injured, but I am not the perpetrator, " the young man said earlier in court, who did not deny that the fateful day was in the hairdresser. He said he wanted a haircut. But he left after his wife told him he was closing. He turned himself in to the police as a witness.
At first, the hairdresser did not recognize him as the aggressor during the interrogation, but later she called him the attacker. According to forensic experts, she suffered from memory lapses after the attack.
The Hradec Králové regional court successively handed down five judgments in the case. At first, he was found guilty twice and sentenced to 16 years in prison, the Supreme Court of Appeal reduced his sentence to 13 years. Uncombed gradually headed for prison twice, but each time after the intervention of the Supreme Court was released. After the ordered replacement of the judicial chamber, repeated acquittals finally fell, the last of which was confirmed by the Supreme Court in March this year.
At the same time, Jiří lněnička, chairman of the board of Appeal, stated in the grounds of his conclusions that this decision was wrong, but, given the procedural situation, he did not have a better option. He said that he had dismissed the prosecutor's appeal against the acquittal, even though her objections were justified.
"The problem of this case is not that there was a lack of evidence, but their evaluation. We believe that a sufficient amount of evidence was collected in the pre-trial proceedings, which would have been sufficient for the admission of guilt in another criminal case, " said lněnička.
But hradecký, as well as the Supreme Court, looked at the case differently and their opinion would probably not change if the acquittal was overturned.
