From Tuesday in the Czech Republic threatens heat, meteorologists warn of fires
The weather warning for high temperatures is valid for Tuesday afternoon for the whole of Bohemia with the exception of the Karlovy Vary region and also for southern and central Moravia.
"Exceptionally, temperatures can exceed 34 degrees Celsius, especially in Central Bohemia," they state.
People are advised to adhere to the drinking regime in the heat and limit the physical load in the midday and afternoon hours.
Due to the warm weather with a minimum of precipitation, there will be a risk of fires starting from Tuesday morning.
Windy weather could contribute to their rapid spread.
The warning of meteorologists about the risk of fires concerns Central Bohemia, including Prague, Liberec, Ústí nad Labem, Karlovy Vary and Pilsen regions.
The fire warning will remain in effect until further notice.
"We do not expect more significant precipitation, which would mitigate the danger, in the north-west and west of Bohemia at least until the end of the week," says the cmmu.
The Prague municipality responded to the warnings of meteorologists with a ban on setting fires in risky places, which is to apply from Tuesday.
People in the capital will not be allowed to set open fires, for example, in parks, gardens or forests, up to a distance of 50 meters from the edge of the forest.
Smoking and the use of pyrotechnics are also prohibited in these places.
The measure will be valid until further notice, said Vít Hofman, a spokesman for the Prague city hall.
The French chef is suing Michelin for removing the star. I suffer from depression, he claims
Renowned French chef Marc Veyrat lost his third Michelin star in January this year, a year after winning it. With the publisher of the red guide, he intends to sue to receive the exact reasons for the degradation. Veyrat also doubts the competence of Michelin inspectors, who, according to him, mistook saffron for cheddar. The first trial is scheduled for November.
The chef of the famous restaurant La Maison de Bois in the alpine region of Upper Savoie lost one of the three Michelin stars in January this year. The publisher of the prestigious guide Le Guide Michelin will be sued, because the conclusion of the commissioners, according to him, was not properly justified. In addition, the removal of the asterisk, according to him, occurred without any notice. "Six months I suffer from depression. How dare you mess with the health of the cooks?"Veyrat said to the commissioners.
Michelin allegedly gave the chef only vague reasons, such as that the chef put Cheddar in the soufflé, which the inspection did not like. "I put saffron in it, and these gentlemen thought it was cheddar, because it was yellow. From the beginning, I have been working with Savoy ingredients with love," he protested against Veyrat's decision. The latter is convinced of the strong incompetence of the Michelin commissioners: "you are scammers who only provoke disputes for commercial reasons."The indignant Veyrat does not understand" how they could afford to say that we put Cheddar in our soufflé". "They also offended our region, my employees were crazy about it. We have eggs from our hens, milk from our own cows, gardeners collect fresh herbs every morning, " he huffed.
The distinguished chef, always with a black hat on his head and dark glasses, is an opponent of the new generation of Michelin commissioners, and therefore calls for the exclusion of his restaurant from the red guide. However, the publisher refuses to do this. "If the business remains open and our inspectors re-select it, we will continue to recommend it," says Gwendal Pullennec, international director of Michelin.
According to Michelin, the chef's lawsuit testifies that he does not yet have any meaningful accusation, and the lawyer will only help him formulate it. "We regret that Mr Veyrat communicates rudely with us. But we will carefully examine his comments, " he said.
In addition to La Maison de bois, Marc veyart owns two more three-star restaurants.
